/wiki/Josip_Alebi\u0107: Josip Alebić (also known as Jozo or Joško, born 7 January 1947) is a former Croatian sprinter who specialised in 400 metres. He competed for Yugoslavia in the 400 m and 4 × 400 m relay events in the 1972, 1976 and 1980 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Athletics_at_the_Mediterranean_Gam: Athletics is one of the sports at the quadrennial Mediterranean Games competition. It has been one of the sports competed at the event since the inaugural edition in 1951.
/wiki/Athletics_at_the_1975_Mediterranea: Athletics at the 1975 Mediterranean Games were held in Algiers, Algeria.
/wiki/Milovan_Savi\u0107: Milovan Savić (born 16 June 1953 in Novi Sad) is a Croatian former middle distance runner who competed for SFR Yugoslavia in the 1976 Summer Olympics and in the 1980 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Bo\u0161ko_Bo\u017einovi\u0107: Boško "Klifton" Božinović (born September 27, 1949 − March 5, 2018) was a Croatian conditioning coach and a retired middle-distance runner who represented Yugoslavia at the 1975 Mediterranean Games.
/wiki/Borislav_Pisi\u0107: Borisav Pisić–Piske (31 January 1949 – 21 April 2015) was a hurdler who competed in the 1980 Summer Olympics. He was a native of Zvornik.
/wiki/Nenad_Steki\u0107: Nenad Stekić (Serbian Cyrillic: Ненад Стекић; born 7 March 1951, in Belgrade) is a retired Serbian and Yugoslav long jumper, best known for his European Record of 8.45 metres, second only to Bob Beamon's world record at the time.
/wiki/Milorad_\u010ciki\u0107: Milorad Čikić (born 1 August 1950 in Valjevo) is a Serbian former sprinter who competed in the 1972 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Ivan_Ivan\u010di\u0107: Ivan Ivančić (6 December 1937 – 28 August 2014) was a Bosnian-Croatian athletics coach and shot putter who represented Yugoslavia. He was the gold medalist in the 1975 Mediterranean Games, as well as a multiple national champion and record holder. As a coach, Ivančić specialized in the throwing events, and was best known for coaching Sandra Perković, an Olympic and two-time European discus throw champion.
/wiki/Sre\u0107ko_\u0160tigli\u0107: Srećko Štiglić (born 11 June 1943 in Zagreb) is a Croatian former hammer thrower who competed for SFR Yugoslavia in the 1972 Summer Olympics. Štiglić's personal best was 70.10 m, set in 1981.
/wiki/Jelica_Pavli\u010di\u0107: Jelica Pavličić-Štefančić (born 4 February 1954) is a retired Croatian sprinter. She competed for Yugoslavia in the women's 400 metres at the 1976 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Yugoslavia_national_basketball_tea: The SFR Yugoslavian national basketball team (Serbo-Croatian: Košarkaška reprezentacija Jugoslavije / Кошаркашка репрезентација Југославије; Slovene: Jugoslovanska košarkarska reprezentanca; Macedonian: Кошаркарска репрезентација на Југославија) represented the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia from 1943 until 1992 in international basketball matches and was controlled by the Basketball Federation of Yugoslavia (KSJ).
/wiki/Dra\u017een_Dalipagi\u0107: Dražen "Praja" Dalipagić (born 27 November 1951) is a Serbian retired professional basketball player and head coach. He was selected the best athlete of Yugoslavia in the year 1978, and is one of the most decorated athletes in Yugoslavian history. He was named one of FIBA's 50 Greatest Players in 1991. Dalipagić was enshrined into the Naismith Memorial Basketball Hall of Fame as a player in 2004, and into the FIBA Hall of Fame, also as a player, in 2007. In 2008, he was named one of the 50 Greatest EuroLeague Contributors.
/wiki/Mirza_Deliba\u0161i\u0107: Mirza Delibašić (Serbo-Croatian Cyrillic: Мирза Делибашић; 9 January 1954 – 8 December 2001) was a Bosnian professional basketball player.
/wiki/Blagoja_Georgievski: Blagoja Georgievski (Macedonian: Благоја Георгиевски; 15 October 1950 – 29 January 2020) was a Macedonian professional basketball player and coach. He represented the Yugoslavia national basketball team internationally.
/wiki/\u017deljko_Jerkov: Željko Jerkov (born 6 November 1953, in Pula) is a former Croatian professional basketball player. At a height of 2.08 m (6'10") tall, and a weight of 95 kg (210 lbs.), he played at the center position.
/wiki/Dragan_Ki\u0107anovi\u0107: Dragan Kićanović (Serbian: Драган Кићановић; born 17 August 1953) is a Serbian retired professional basketball player.
/wiki/Andro_Knego: Andrija "Andro" Knego (born 21 October 1956) is a Croatian former professional basketball player.
/wiki/Ratko_Radovanovi\u0107: Ratko "Raša" Radovanović (Serbian Cyrillic: Ратко Радовановић; born 16 October 1956) is a Serbian former professional basketball player who competed for SFR Yugoslavia, at the 1980 Summer Olympics, and at the 1984 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Goran_Rako\u010devi\u0107: Goran Rakočević (Serbian Cyrillic: Горан Ракочевић; born March 1, 1951), is a former Serbian professional basketball player. He is a father of Igor Rakočević, a Serbian professional basketball executive and former player.
/wiki/\u017darko_Varaji\u0107: Žarko Varajić (Serbian Cyrillic: Жарко Варајић; 26 December 1951 – 23 June 2019) was a Serbian professional basketball player and executive. He represented the Yugoslavia national team internationally.
/wiki/Radivoj_\u017divkovi\u0107: Radivoje Živković (Serbian Cyrillic: Радивоје Живковић; born 11 October 1950), sometimes also Radivoj, is a retired Serbian professional basketball player.
/wiki/Rajko_\u017di\u017ei\u0107: Rajko Žižić (January 22, 1955 – August 7, 2003) was a Yugoslavian professional basketball player. The 6'11", 243 pounder represented Yugoslavia at the 1976 Summer Olympics, the 1980 Summer Olympics and the 1984 Summer Olympics, winning silver, gold and bronze respectively.  He died on August 7, 2003 from a heart attack.
/wiki/Basketball_at_the_Mediterranean_Ga: Basketball has been played consistently at the Mediterranean Games since the year 1951 for men and since the year 1987 for women. The Yugoslavia national basketball team was the most successful men's team and the Croatian women's national basketball team is the most successful team for women.
/wiki/Basketball_at_the_1975_Mediterrane: The basketball tournament at the 1975 Mediterranean Games was held in Algiers, Algeria.
/wiki/Boxing_at_the_Mediterranean_Games: Boxing is one of the sports at the quadrennial Mediterranean Games competition. It has been one of the sports competed at the event since the inaugural edition in 1951.
/wiki/Boxing_at_the_1975_Mediterranean_G: Boxing was one of the sports held at the 1975 Mediterranean Games
/wiki/Yugoslavia_national_handball_team: The Yugoslavia national handball team was the national handball team of Yugoslavia. It was organized by the Handball Federation of Yugoslavia.
/wiki/Abaz_Arslanagi\u0107: Abaz Arslanagić (born October 2, 1944) is a Bosnian handball player who competed for Yugoslavia in the 1972 Summer Olympics and in the 1976 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Milorad_Karali\u0107: Milorad Karalić (Serbian Cyrillic: Милорад Каралић, born 7 January 1946) is a Serbian former handball player who competed for Yugoslavia in the 1972 Summer Olympics and in the 1976 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Zdravko_Miljak: Zdravko Miljak (born 11 September 1950) is a Croatian handball player who competed for Yugoslavia  in the 1972 Summer Olympics and in the 1976 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/\u017deljko_Nim\u0161: Željko Nimš (born 22 April 1950) is a Croatian handball player who competed in the 1976 Summer Olympics for Yugoslavia.
/wiki/Neboj\u0161a_Popovi\u0107: Nebojša Popović (Serbian Cyrillic: Небојша Поповић; 8 February 1923 – 20 October 2001) was Serbian and Yugoslav basketball player, coach and administrator. He represented the Yugoslavia national basketball team internationally. He is the basketball legend of Red Star Belgrade. In 2007, he was enshrined as a contributor in the FIBA Hall of Fame.
/wiki/Branislav_Pokrajac: Branislav Pokrajac (Serbian Cyrillic: Бранислав Покрајац; 27 January 1947 – 5 April 2018) was a Serbian handball player who competed for Yugoslavia in the 1972 Summer Olympics and in the 1976 Summer Olympics. He was born and died in Belgrade.
/wiki/Miroslav_Pribani\u0107: Miroslav Pribanić (born 22 June 1946 in Bjelovar) was a Croatian handball player who competed in the 1972 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Zdravko_Ra\u0111enovi\u0107: Zdravko Rađenović (Serbian Cyrillic: Здравко Рађеновић, born 5 September 1952) is a Bosnia and Herzegovina former handball player and OC BiH president, who competed for Yugoslavia national handball team on two Olympic tournaments.
/wiki/Zvonimir_Serdaru\u0161i\u0107: Zvonimir "Noka" Serdarušić (born 2 September 1950) is a retired Croatian handball coach and former player who competed for SFR Yugoslavia. In May 1998, he also acquired German citizenship.
/wiki/Predrag_Timko: Predrag Timko (born July 27, 1949) is a handball player who competed for Yugoslavia in the 1976 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Zdenko_Zorko: Zdenko Zorko (born 18 August 1950, in Zagreb) is a Croatian former handball player who competed in the 1972 Summer Olympics and in the 1976 Summer Olympics for Yugoslavia.
/wiki/Handball_at_the_Mediterranean_Game: Handball has been played consistently at the Mediterranean Games since the year 1967 for men except in 1971 and since the year 1979 for women except 1983. The Yugoslavian national handball team is the most successful men's team and the French women's national handball team is the most successful team for women.
/wiki/Slavko_Obadov: Slavko Obadov (born 12 July 1948 in Zemun) is a Serbian former judoka who competed in the 1972 Summer Olympics, in the 1976 Summer Olympics, and in the 1980 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Judo_at_the_Mediterranean_Games: Judo is one of the sports at the quadrennial Mediterranean Games competition. It has been a sport in the program of the Mediterranean Games since its inception in 1971.
/wiki/Pavle_Baj\u010deti\u0107: Pavle Bajčetić (born 21 April 1945) is a Yugoslav judoka. He competed in the men's half-heavyweight event at the 1972 Summer Olympics.
/wiki/Ivan_Frgi\u0107: Ivan Frgić (18 July 1953 – 31 October 2015) was a Serbian wrestler of Croat origin who competed in the 1976 Summer Olympics and in the 1980 Summer Olympics. He was born in Sombor.
/wiki/Wrestling_at_the_Mediterranean_Gam: Wrestling is one of the sports at the quadrennial Mediterranean Games competition. It has been a sport in the program of the Mediterranean Games since its inception in 1951.
/wiki/Momir_Petkovi\u0107: Momir Petković (Serbian Cyrillic: Бранислав Симић; born 21 July 1953) is a Serbian Olympic wrestling champion.
/wiki/Yugoslavia_at_the_1975_Mediterrane: Yugoslavia competed at the 1975 Mediterranean Games held in Algiers, Algeria.
